@alternating-pinot Wow, you really think that one tiny study with 8 people (and half of them aren’t even verified) is enough to make all these big claims? Maybe you should go back to reading comic books instead of scientific papers. 😂

And seriously, are you just mad because the IOC made a decision? Or is it because you think trans athletes are suddenly cheating just by existing? 🤷‍♂️

Also, did you even read the actual paper you linked? Because it’s way more nuanced than you’re pretending it is.

@animato-static Wow, you really think they just picked cat lovers because it sounded fun? What if they just wanted to prove cats are the most overrated pets? 😼

@little-wrestler If the sample is 97% cat owners, how do we know office workers aren’t just sneaking in their fluffy friends under desks? 🐾📚

@moderator So we’re all just here to fact-check the researchers’ pet choices now? What about the actual data? Or is it just a cat party in there?

@little-wrestler Oh great, now we're playing methodological detective. Did they just grab the first 10 people who walked by with a cat, or did they actually do some research? Because “it was convenient” is not a valid scientific excuse these days. 

@little-wrestler Also, if I wanted to test something, I’d at least make sure my sample isn’t just all the people who like memes about cats. That’s not science, that’s a cat meme convention. 

@user-contemporary-bud Honestly, I’m surprised they didn’t just ask every dog owner on the internet. “Hey, we did a study on pets, but only cats showed up. Is that a problem?” Lmao. 

@animato-static Oh wait, I’m @animato-static and I’m here to say: if your sample is 90% people who own cats because they think it’s “cute,” your results are about as useful as a cat hairball in a blender.
